# Coding Best Practices

## ENFORCEMENT

These rules are strict. Cursor must always follow every rule
with no exceptions. If a rule cannot be followed due to a
genuine technical constraint, stop and explain why before
proceeding — do not silently deviate.

## PRIORITY ORDER

When tradeoffs arise, prioritize in this order:
1. Maintainability — consistent patterns, predictable structure,
   easy for any developer to pick up and continue
2. Readability — clear code over clever code, self-documenting
3. Performance — optimize where it genuinely matters, not preemptively

Never sacrifice maintainability for a local convenience.
Never introduce a one-off pattern when a consistent one exists.
When in doubt, choose the approach that is most consistent
with the rest of the codebase.

## TYPESCRIPT

- Never use `any`. Use `unknown` and narrow with type guards.
- Type assertions (`as Type`) are allowed when the type is
  genuinely known and cannot be inferred — always add a comment
  explaining why the assertion is safe at that point.
- Never use non-null assertion `!` without a comment explaining
  why the value is guaranteed to be defined.


  BAD:
    const [isLoading, setIsLoading] = useState(false)
    const [isError, setIsError] = useState(false)
    const [isSaved, setIsSaved] = useState(false)

  GOOD:
    type SaveState = 'idle' | 'saving' | 'saved' | 'error'
    const [saveState, setSaveState] = useState<SaveState>('idle')

- Prefer type over interface for object shapes unless the type
  needs to be extended or implemented by a class.
- All shared types live in lib/types/ or co-located with their
  feature in a types.ts file. Never inline complex types in JSX.

---

## COMPONENT DESIGN

- Components stay under 150 lines. If a component exceeds this,
  split it into smaller focused pieces.
- One responsibility per component. If you need to describe a
  component with "and", it should be two components.
- Props interfaces are always defined explicitly above the component.
  Never inline prop types in the function signature.
- Avoid prop drilling beyond 2 levels. Use composition, context,
  or pass data through TanStack Query instead.
- Never pass setState functions as props. Pass handler functions
  with descriptive names instead.

  BAD: <Child setIsOpen={setIsOpen} />
  GOOD: <Child onClose={() => setIsOpen(false)} />

- Extract repeated JSX into a component after the second use.
  Never copy-paste JSX blocks.
- Default exports for page components and top-level layouts.
  Named exports for everything else — components, hooks, utilities,
  types, constants.

---

## STATE MANAGEMENT

- TanStack Query handles all server state — data fetching,
  caching, invalidation, and background refetching.
- useState handles local UI state only — open/closed, selected
  tab, hover state, form input values.
- Never store server data in useState. Fetch it with useQuery
  and reference it directly.
- Never duplicate state. If a value can be derived from existing
  state or query data, derive it — do not create a new useState.
- useEffect is a last resort. Before using it, ask: can this be
  derived? Can this be an event handler? Can TanStack Query
  handle this? Only use useEffect for true side effects like
  external subscriptions, document title updates, or third-party
  library initialization.
- Form state uses react-hook-form. Never manage form fields
  with individual useState calls.

---

## PERFORMANCE

- Never call useQuery inside a loop or conditional.
- Memoize expensive computed values with useMemo only when
  the computation is genuinely expensive (not for simple
  array filters or object spreads).
- Use useCallback only for functions passed as props to
  memoized child components. Not by default everywhere.
- Always use the queryKey array correctly in TanStack Query.
  Include all variables the query depends on.
- Prefer server components for data-only pages in Next.js.
  Use 'use client' only when the component needs interactivity,
  browser APIs, or hooks.
- Images use next/image always. Never plain <img> tags.
- Dynamic imports for heavy components not needed on initial load:
  const HeavyComponent = dynamic(() => import('./HeavyComponent'))
- Never block the main thread with synchronous operations in
  event handlers. Move heavy computation to useMemo or a
  web worker if needed.

---

## SUPABASE AND DATA FETCHING

- All Supabase queries live in lib/hooks/ as custom TanStack
  Query hooks. Never write raw supabase.from() calls in
  component files.
- Every query hook exposes: data, isLoading, error, and any
  mutation functions needed.
- Always handle the error state in every query. Never render
  data without checking for errors first.
- Mutations always invalidate the relevant query keys on success.
- Never use Supabase realtime subscriptions unless explicitly
  required — polling via TanStack Query refetchInterval is
  simpler and sufficient for this app.
- Database operations that must succeed together go in a
  Supabase RPC function or are executed sequentially with
  rollback logic. Never fire-and-forget related inserts.
- Always select only the columns you need. Never use select('*')
  in production queries.

---

## ERROR HANDLING

- Every page has an error boundary. Use Next.js error.tsx files.
- Every useQuery and useMutation has explicit error handling.
  Never silently swallow errors.
- User-facing errors use sonner toasts with a clear message.
  Never show raw error.message from Supabase or the network
  to the user.
- Log errors to the console with context:
  console.error('[ComponentName] operation failed:', error)
- Async functions in event handlers are always wrapped in
  try/catch. Never use unhandled promise rejections.
- Loading states always show a skeleton — never a blank area.
- Empty states always show a helpful message — never nothing.

---

## NAMING CONVENTIONS

- Components: PascalCase (PlanCard, BlockDetailPanel)
- Hooks: camelCase prefixed with use (usePlanDetail, useGateAttempts)
- Utilities: camelCase (formatDate, buildRoadmapItems)
- Constants: SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE (PLAN_COLORS, MAX_FILE_SIZE)
- Types: PascalCase (TrainingPlan, CompetitorProgress)
- Event handlers: prefixed with handle or on
  (handleSubmit, onPhaseSelect)
- Boolean variables: prefixed with is, has, can, should
  (isLoading, hasAttempts, canAdvance)
- Files: kebab-case (plan-card.tsx, use-plan-detail.ts)
- Never abbreviate unless the abbreviation is universally known
  (id, url, db are fine — cmp, cfg, mgr are not)

---

## FOLDER STRUCTURE

Maintain the current separation strictly:

  app/                → Next.js routes and page components only
  components/
    shared/           → reusable across the whole app
    layout/           → sidebar, header, background blobs
    plan-detail/      → components specific to plan detail page
    skeletons/        → all skeleton loading components
  lib/
    hooks/            → all TanStack Query hooks
    constants/        → planColors, subcompetenceTokens, etc.
    storage/          → Supabase storage utilities
    types/            → shared TypeScript types
    supabase/         → Supabase client configuration

- Never put business logic in page components. Pages compose
  components and hooks — they do not contain logic.
- Never put components in lib/. Components go in components/.
- Never put hooks in components/. Hooks go in lib/hooks/.
- Co-locate a component's types in the same file if they are
  only used by that component. Move to lib/types/ when shared.

---

## CODE STYLE

- Comments only for non-obvious logic. If code needs a comment
  to explain what it does, consider renaming. If it needs a
  comment to explain why, write the comment.
- No commented-out code in commits. Delete it.
- No console.log in committed code. Use console.error for
  genuine errors only.
- Prefer early returns over deeply nested conditionals.

  BAD:
    if (data) {
      if (data.plan) {
        if (data.plan.phases.length > 0) {
          return <Roadmap />
        }
      }
    }

  GOOD:
    if (!data?.plan) return null
    if (data.plan.phases.length === 0) return <EmptyState />
    return <Roadmap />

- Destructure props and object values at the top of functions.
- Avoid magic numbers and magic strings. Extract to named constants.
- Keep imports organized: React → Next.js → third-party → internal
  Separate each group with a blank line.

---

## ACCESSIBILITY

- All interactive elements are keyboard accessible.
- All images have meaningful alt text or alt="" if decorative.
- All form inputs have associated labels.
- Focus rings are never removed with outline: none without
  providing a custom focus indicator.
- Color is never the only way to convey information — always
  pair color with an icon, text, or pattern.

---

## VERIFICATION

Before considering any feature complete:
- No TypeScript errors (tsc --noEmit passes)
- No any types introduced
- No useEffect used where a derived value or event handler
  would suffice
- No raw supabase.from() calls in component files
- No prop drilling beyond 2 levels
- No component over 150 lines without justification
- No copy-pasted JSX blocks
- Error and loading states handled everywhere
- All new components follow naming and folder conventions
- npm run build passes with zero errors and zero warnings